{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.04,0.33,0.46,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1039"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37239"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl is brought to the Emergency Department by her parents after ingesting an unknown quantity of household bleach. The mother reports finding the child with an empty bottle of bleach, and the child is currently complaining of a burning sensation in the mouth and throat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe child has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears restless and irritable with signs of dehydration. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 115/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are no other signs of trauma or injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activated charcoal","Induction of emesis","Gastric lavage","Symptom-specific supportive care","N-acetylcysteine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe child has presented with significant ingestion of bleach, which may cause corrosive gastrointestinal injury and systemic effects, such as metabolic acidosis, hypernatraemia and hyperchloraemia. There is no specific treatment recommended for bleach ingestion; \u003Cstrong\u003Esymptom-specific supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E involving treating any resulting complications of ingestion is the primary management option. Patients should also undergo endoscopy to assess the severity of gastrointestinal injury and guide therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUse of proton-pump inhibitors and histamine H\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E-receptor antagonists to reduce gastric acid secretion is not uncommon. However, studies have demonstrated no benefit and therefore, their use is not routinely recommended. There is limited evidence for corticosteroids to reduce risk of oesophageal stricture development - a decision for their use should be made in consultation with a gastroenterologist to treat specific pathology. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering activated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in cases of ingestion of certain drugs and toxins within the early hours of ingestion. However, bleach does not bind to activated charcoal, and it is therefore not indicated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInducing emesis\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended in the management of poisoning due to its potential complications, including aspiration pneumonia and respiratory distress. It is also contraindicated in cases of ingestion of corrosive substances, such as bleach, due to the risk of further damage to the oesophagus and stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in the management of poisoning due to potential complications, including aspiration, perforation, and bleeding. It is also contraindicated in cases of ingestion of corrosive substances, such as bleach, due to the risk of further damage to the oesophagus and stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering N-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in cases of paracetamol overdose, which can cause liver failure. It is not indicated in the management of poisoning due to bleach ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptom-specific supportive care is the treatment of choice for bleach ingestion.","Induction of emesis and gastric lavage are contraindicated in corrosive ingestions due to risk of re-exposure to the caustic agent.","Children with symptoms after corrosive ingestion should undergo oesophagoscopy within 24 hours."],"references":["Caustic ingestions. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Nickson C. Corrosive ingestion. LITFL. Available from: https://litfl.com/corrosive-ingestion-ccc/","Slaughter RJ, Watts M, Vale JA, Grieve JR, Schep LJ. The clinical toxicology of sodium hypochlorite. Clin Toxicol (Phila). 2019 May;57(5):303-311. doi: 10.1080/15563650.2018.1543889. Epub 2019 Jan 28. PMID: 30689457.","Benzoni T, Hatcher JD. Bleach Toxicity. 2022 Oct 16. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722950."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12640"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T11:14:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T11:17:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","